1.7 million consensus, assuming a 8% standard deviation around that.

Since April 2020 the annual rate for housing starts has been trending upwards, with March 2021 reaching 1.739 million. If the figure continues to trend upward there is a good chance that the figure will be more than 1.6 million. However, from January to February of 2021 the annual rate dropped by around 0.2 million, so if another drop were to occur the figure could fall below 1.6 million. Generally speaking, it seems like April's annual rate will not drop but instead continue to trend upward.
A time-series forecast indicated values upwards of 1.6, but there is enough uncertainty to downplay the max outcome.

I appreciated @pietrokc's prior analysis. I took a slightly different angle, looking at changes vs recent levels: If you look at the data since 1959, typically the next month is about the same as the prior three months housing starts with an 8% standard deviation around that. Given the recent levels (1.604 over last 3 months), as well as the consensus call for march housing at 1.62, that means there is a little more than a 50% chance of 1.6 million starts, but also very low chances of anything less than 1.2. By my analysis, a 1.4 would be a -1.6Z event, meaning a 6% probability. That's all a pure outside view. The inside view is also supportive of that given fiscal stimulus and continued progress on vaccine rollout.

The first step to forecasting a question is the understand the question! In this case, there are three statistics that revolve around housing starts. 1) Building permits for new homes 2) Housing Starts 3) Housing Completions
Base Rate: Using regression analysis of the last 10 years of FRED housing start data, we should expect April 2021 housing starts to be 1,497,756. From Excel, the formula for new housing starts is:

Main driver is low interest rates. I do not foresee a significant change in rates before April. Housing starts in Dec 2020 were rate of 1,338,000 and in Nov 1,195,000. Supply of existing home in December was at record low, causing new home starts to increase. Building permits, a strong indicator of new starts, in December 2020 were 17.3 percent higher than in Dec 2019. This all points to strong April new starts. I also do not believe we will see a near-term housing bubble burst. 2008 housing bubble is not a good comparison to today's conditions.

Outside View: April 2020 was the recent low, at .934M units. Previous data showed: 2019: 1.267M, 2018: 1.269M, 2017: 1.15M. However, there has been a significant recovery and trend up, with Jun 20 at 1.265M, Nov 20 at 1.578M and Dec 20 at 1.669M. Dec is historically an average or perhaps slightly low month for starts.

While the rate of housing starts is currently reaching new highs, I doubt it will continue into April. The current numbers are likely a response to the abnormally low numbers at the start of the COVID pandemic. Therefore, I suspect these numbers will level out and return to a normal rate of growth within a couple of months. Housing starts totaled between 1.043 million and 1.269 million for April 2014-2019. Assuming that housing starts will continue to grow, as they historically have, and that there will be a slightly higher number than usual given the results of the COVID pandemic, between 1.4 and 1.6 million is the likeliest result with between 1.2 and 1.4 million also being significantly possible.

The bubble is unlikely to pop until inflation rises significantly, and that is unlikely before April. I think inflation will rise a bit, maybe 2.5% or 3% this year come up and I doubt that will happen and I doubt the effects will take place before April. Until and after that, lots of easy money.

"Use of seasonally adjusted time series data can be misleading because a seasonally adjusted series contains both the trend-cycle component and the error component. As such, what appear to be "downturns" or "upturns" may actually be randomness in the data. For this reason, if the purpose is finding turning points in a series, using the trend-cycle component is recommended rather than the seasonally adjusted data." https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seasonal_adjustment#Shortcomings_of_using_seasonally_adjusted_data

After some thoughtful feedback from GJO teammates, I'm adjusting my forecast to a slightly less optimistic assessment. Given my research, I still believe that April 2021 will see housing starts in excess of historic levels for April. Increases in demand, in supplies and reduced inventory should provide good numbers, but I think skilled labor is still going to be a problem coming out of a projected COVID recovery.

- Baseline: The average rate of home starts in April from 2010 to 2020 was 985k. However, the range was large, running as high as 1.269M in 2018 and as low as 554k in 2011. - Monthly starts have held above 1M since May 2020. - The FED has indicated the exceptionally low interest rate environment likely will persist through at least 2021.

In the last 5 years, new starts have only been less than 1M once--in Apr of 2020 immediately on the heals of the COVID crisis in March. They have fallen between 1M-1.2M approximately 20 times and between 1.2 and 1.4 more than 30 times and above 1.4M about 5 times. Limiting the data to Jan 18 forward, the avg has been 1285. Even the COVID shock only lasted two months and the estimates have rebounded to the 1.2-1.4 range since. (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/HOUST / https://tradingeconomics.com/united-states/housing-starts). Add to that the higher than expected growth in existing home prices (https://www.zillow.com/research/expert-predictions-zhpe-q32020-27999/) and historically low interest rates, and the incentive exists for new starts. There are however, some barriers to new starts (https://www.zillow.com/research/zillow-weekly-market-report-27151/) such as building material price shocks spurred by COVID that could keep new starts a bit lower than expected. Also, significant increases in mortgage rates (perhaps post election?) could stifle new home investment as well.

• The decade high for housing starts was in January 2020 (1.617M), as U.S. recovered from 2007-2009 recession. From April-July 2020, they recovered better than expected to 1.492M (22.6% increase, the largest gain since October 2016), but have fallen 5.1% in August 2020. Building permits issuance also increased to 1.495M at an annualized rate. • Housing starts rose the most during the summer in the Midwest (28.4%); however, the Midwest also is grappling with a seeming second wave of COVID, which could make Americans there less likely to break ground on a new construction. • With a second wave of COVID likely in many regions, the economy could suffer another setback this winter. Recently, there have been a few high-profile layoffs (Disney, American Airlines), and the two-month stalemate in stimulus talks has not helped boost confidence in the economy.

- Housing Starts in the United States averaged 1428.28 Thousand units from 1959 until 2020 - Housing starts in the US fell 5.1 percent to an annualized rate of 1,416 thousand in August of 2020, below market forecasts of 1,478 thousand and following a downwardly revised 1,492 thousand in July - Peak homeownership in the US was 69% in 2004. - Homeownership today is at 67% - Interest rates are at all-time lows making the cost of ownership cheaper. - COVID = more time at home - Housing start trend line is up. - Unemployement due to COVID will reduce buyers and we are near historic homeownership.

Housing start graphs show a steady increase in housing starts since the 2008 recession save the recent dip from acute problems created by coronavirus. The conditions underpinning the housing market appear to be 3-fold - unemployment rate, mortgage rates, housing prices. Unemployment rate is approximately 8% range and by most indications should continue to lower in the next 6 months regardless of outcome of the election. This would provide wage support for housing purchases which should keep demand for housing high. Mortgage rates are at historic lows and the FED is projecting to maintain interest rates at or near zero into or through 2022. That would provide a low borrowing cost for home purchases and should maintain strong demand for purchases. A potential negative for the housing market is the near all-time high in median prices nationwide. Multiple factors seem to be contributing to continued demand driven price increases - stimulus payments keeping individuals out of major personal debt, desire to move into larger living arrangements in projection of continued remote working, and extremely lost cost of borrowing. However, there is a limit to the price affordability compared to the wages. If the housing prices reach that price point demand will plateau. One last consideration might serve as a brake on purchases - mortgage defaults. Current mortgage default rates are falling, however signs show this is being driven more by federal protection through forbearance programs which are due to expire in March 2021. Current housing starts are just over 1.4 million and I evaluate the combination of factors above should lead to slow and steady rise over the next six months.

Demand should be up, cash sloshing around all over the place, unemployed provide readily available labor, states no longer inhibiting construction due to Covid-19. Fires, floods and storms have reduced existing stock further fueling demand.

I tried to think of math-y ways to come up with an outside view for the base rate, but got frustrated. I looked at the FRED graph for housing starts for the period of 2010-Aug 2020. The interesting thing was that there's a clear visual pattern: every year, the line goes up and down in clumps of spikes (wish I could paste in a screenshot but can't). But in addition to that the overall trend is that the number of housing starts goes gradually up, year on year. So even though the housing starts "crashed" in April 2020 relative to the rest of 2020 so far, the April 2020 housing starts are higher than, say, anytime in 2011-2012.
Since 1959 housing starts have averaged about 1.43m per month. Incidentally, April is the lowest month of the year on average but is still above 1.4m.
